args: The water's flow is calm and gentle,\nthe stirring moss fresh and green...
A fine place, this country—rich in natural\nsplendor and human kindness both.
I tried cooking the rice the way you\nrequested. Does it suit you?
Thank you. Ahhh... The smell of burned\nsoy sauce is so wonderfully fragrant.
I believe it's almost time for your next\ndance performance, yes? I shall be\nrooting for you.
I-it's all right. Just a sudden stress pain.\nCompletely normal, I assure you.
He seems to have gotten a bit better since\nhe came here. He's like a sick kid sent to\nrest'n recover by breathin' our good air.
A kid? I dunno, he gives me more of an\nold hermit vibe.
Might I have some tea?\nAh, thank you. *slurp*
By the way, are my rice crackers done?\nAnd my kuzukiri.
I just gave you the rice crackers—\nand you never asked for any kuzukiri!

Ha ha. Yeah, he's got kind of an ol' geezer
vibe. But man, all it takes is talking about
the you-know-what dance to make him
sweat.

He really scares easily, huh?
He might be a master dancer,
but he wouldn't last an hour on
the battlefield.
Ha ha. Or so you'd think!
Uh, care to explain the maniacal grin?
Eventually, Ranzal came to understand\nthe meaning behind Mitsuhide's smile.
Whoa! We've got our hands full with this\none! Its scales are so hard we can't even\ndamage it!
Hanabusa! You go behind it, and I'll—
What're you doin'?! Attacking it from the\nfront ain't gonna do any good!
Oww! I'm bleeding! I'm bleeding!\nI'm so sorry!
If you're not gonna help us beat it,\njust run with yer tail tucked already!
Give me your honest opinion on this,\nRanzal. You think we can beat it?
We don't stand a chance. Yer tough,\nbut this is beyond us, even as a tag-team.
This ain't no ordinary fiend. If we're not\ncareful, we'll all end up dead.
You heard the man. If we're not careful,\nwe're gonna die. Do you want to die?
No! I don't wanna die!\nI DON'T WANNA DIE!
Then you'd better get a hold of yourself.\nWe're about to lose to this thing because\nof you buckling under pressure.
You've got two choices:\nstand tall or prepare to fall.
So why not show us what you're REALLY\ncapable of?
I am. Lady Mitsuhide's divine ki,\nlike the majesty of a holy mountain,\nhas opened my eyes.
If we do not defeat this fiend here,\nwe will not live to see tomorrow.\nThis may be my final performance.
So I will show you the true essence of\ndance—and accept whatever fate has in\nstore for me.
Damn, he dodged those attacks at the\nlast second without ever leavin' the\nground!
This is how we dance in Hinomoto. One\nmust ever remain anchored to the earth.\nAnd...
Wait, when'd he get behind it?!
He weaves speed with silence, rending\nhis foes asunder like a kamaitachi.
The time has come for you to release your\ngrip upon this earthly existence. Allow me\nto usher you unto the world beyond.
Can you weather the dazzling light of the\nmoon, streaming down from the heavens?
I can't believe it... How'd he beat\nsomethin' that strong all alone?
I apologize for causing you trouble.
Nah, you saved our bacon! But were my\neyes playin' tricks on me, or what?
Did the castle's biggest coward just thrash\na fiend without so much as flinchin'?
Hanabusa never used to be a coward.
We're all shaped by the sum of our\nexperiences. Surely the same goes for you.
He didn't end up cowardly and\nshort-tempered because he was\nweak. On the contrary, actually.
The weight of expectation ate away at\nhis heart—strong as it was—leaving the\nbroken man you see before you.
If what we just saw was his true strength,\nthen what in blazes happened to this guy?
